\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3}{\ignorespaces Time evolution of the standard deviation of the first order observable ${\cal  J}_z$, as defined in Eq.~\eqref  {eq:variance_z}, for $N=10^8$ and $\gamma _+/\gamma _-=0.997$. The perturbative solution is taken from the approximation in Eq.~\eqref  {eq:variance_z}, $\sigma _{{\cal  J}_z}=\sqrt  {N/4+\gamma _{\rm  tot}N^2t}$, whereas the numerical solution is obtained with the second-order approximation method, introduced in Sec.~\ref {sec:2ndorder}. We highlight the departure from the spin projection noise at $t\gtrsim t_{\rm  diss}$ and the breakdown of the perturbative solution at $t\gtrsim (N\gamma _{\rm  net})^{-1}$.}}{10}{figure.3}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:sigma_z}{{3}{10}{Time evolution of the standard deviation of the first order observable ${\cal J}_z$, as defined in Eq.~\eqref {eq:variance_z}, for $N=10^8$ and $\gamma _+/\gamma _-=0.997$. The perturbative solution is taken from the approximation in Eq.~\eqref {eq:variance_z}, $\sigma _{{\cal J}_z}=\sqrt {N/4+\gamma _{\rm tot}N^2t}$, whereas the numerical solution is obtained with the second-order approximation method, introduced in Sec.~\ref {sec:2ndorder}. We highlight the departure from the spin projection noise at $t\gtrsim t_{\rm diss}$ and the breakdown of the perturbative solution at $t\gtrsim (N\gamma _{\rm net})^{-1}$}{figure.3}{}}
