\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {11}{\ignorespaces Parametric dependence of the experimental sensitivity to the C$\nu $B overdensity parameter $\delta _\nu $. {\it  Left}: Dependence on the spin ensemble radius $R$. Here, we illustrate that, despite a weaker scaling at large $R$, choosing the optimal energy splitting $\omega ^\star _0$, as given by Eq.~\eqref  {eq:wo_opt} for a fixed radius $R$, yields a better sensitivity to $\delta _\nu $ than choosing a fixed splitting with $B<1$~T. See the main text for a detailed explanation of the scaling behaviours with $R$. {\it  Right}: Dependence on the transverse coherence time $T_2$, for both a quantum-limited experiment and a SQUID-noise-dominated experiment with ${\cal  F}_{\rm  SQUID}=50$.}}{21}{figure.11}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:deltaR_scaling}{{11}{21}{Parametric dependence of the experimental sensitivity to the C$\nu $B overdensity parameter $\delta _\nu $. {\it Left}: Dependence on the spin ensemble radius $R$. Here, we illustrate that, despite a weaker scaling at large $R$, choosing the optimal energy splitting $\omega ^\star _0$, as given by Eq.~\eqref {eq:wo_opt} for a fixed radius $R$, yields a better sensitivity to $\delta _\nu $ than choosing a fixed splitting with $B<1$~T. See the main text for a detailed explanation of the scaling behaviours with $R$. {\it Right}: Dependence on the transverse coherence time $T_2$, for both a quantum-limited experiment and a SQUID-noise-dominated experiment with ${\cal F}_{\rm SQUID}=50$}{figure.11}{}}
